{
  "doc_id": "28371",
  "text": "The native bone tissue extracellular matrix (ECM) is mainly composed of carbonated apatite nanocrystals (2-5 nm wide and 70 nm long) and collagen type I fibrous matrix (50-500-nm diameter) [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Considering the structural features of bone ECM, nanofibrous materials containing bioceramic nanoparticles can be served as ideal scaffolding materials for promoting osteoblast proliferation and infiltration in bone tissue engineering applications. Till date, different methods such as drawing, thermally induced phase separation, molecular self-assembly, and electrospinning have been introduced and studied to produce nanofibers. Among them, electrospinning is the most widely applied technique for generating nanoparticles embedded nanofibrous scaffolds due to its ease of use and relatively low-cost instrumental setup [4] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
